  "prompt": "What were the main arguments of each of the dissenting justices against the ruling in favor of same-sex marriages?",
  "response": "In the landmark Obergefell v. Hodges Supreme Court case in 2015, which legalized same-sex marriage nationwide, there were four dissenting justices: Chief Justice John Roberts, and Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and Samuel Alito. Each wrote their own dissenting opinion, but their key arguments generally centered on:\n\n1. Chief Justice Roberts argued:\n- The Constitution does not address same-sex marriage\n- The decision was an act of judicial activism, not constitutional interpretation\n- The court was inappropriately creating a new right rather than interpreting existing law\n- This decision should have been left to democratic processes and state legislatures\n\n2. Justice Scalia strongly criticized the majority's reasoning:\n- The decision was a \"judicial Putsch\" (coup)\n- The court was substituting its own judgment for democratic decision-making\n- The Constitution says nothing about marriage rights for same-sex couples\n\n3. Justice Thomas emphasized:\n- The Constitution does not guarantee a right to marriage\n- The decision undermined democratic self-governance\n- The ruling misunderstood the meaning of liberty and constitutional rights\n\n4. Justice Alito argued:\n- The decision would be used to marginalize those with traditional religious views\n- It represented a radical social redefinition of marriage\n- It potentially threatened religious freedom\n\nThese were their primary constitutional and philosophical objections to the ruling.",
